<br>
++++++<br>
Part 1: pre-50, especially pre-50 AND pre-Kunark....<br>
Casters were VERY over-powered.  Melees had crap weapons (yaks).  A necro could solo the LGuk Lord room....meanwhile a group of 6 melees would wipe if they were foolish enough to try the same.   King room group only wanted pet-casters and healers....melees or any class (even warriors) were unwelcome.  Oh, I remember those ugly days of caster-farmers all too well.<br>
<br>
++++++<br>
Part 2: current state of affairs:<br>
Melees got far better weapons and gear.<br>
In a grind, paladins typically do 40-50 dps (more if its undead), warriors 50, rangers 55, monks 70, rogues about 90-100.  Casters are lucky to do 30 dps...Only the mage epic pet is effective over the long-haul.<br>
<br>
Pathing is so crappy, and MOB-AoE spells so prevalent, that casters are prohibited from using pets on most raids.<br>
<br>
Wizards got great new bane spells, and specialized spells for killing dragons, etc.  AA points help wizards (and other casters) a lot. Wizards especially can now do incredible damage in brief times....like 10k in 30 seconds.  Wizards therefore get a great niche in raids.  Their evac capability and their porting abilities greatly aides their group-friendliness.<br>
<br>
AE groups emerge into reality.  Groups of wizards+chanter+cleric+tank puller (paladin is best) can clean up the exp now in fast-spawn areas.  After all the Luclin zone nerfs, Acrylia, HS and FG remain as great AE locations.  As a result of AE groups, wizards, chanters and clerics now can now reap in exp far faster than any other class.  Necros, mages, druids, shaman, and the non-plate melee classes are not well-suited for these AE groups, and are...well... rather screwed.<br>
<br>
++++++<br>
Summary of class balance, current state of affairs....<br>
<br>
Warriors:  with defensive ability, they own raid tankage.  Good for raids, exp groups, AE groups.  Member of the "holy trinity" (cleric/chanter/warrior).  Crappy AA advancement.  Many new good Luclin weapons.<br>
<br>
Paladins:  with recent class upgrade, they rock.  Great fit in raids (patch heals, LOH cycles, add tankage).  Great in single groups (tankage, stuns, patch heals).  Best pull class for AE groups. Good spells (buffage, heals, haste, undeads).  Very good at crowd control. Great AA advancement opportunity.  Many new good weapons.<br>
<br>
SKs: Best at grind tankage (lifetap self-healage).  Good pullers.  Good for raids.  Some decent spells.  Good AA advancement opportunity.  Many new good weapons.<br>
<br>
Rangers: Good damage dealers.  Good fit in raids.  Acceptable tankage class in many one-group grinds - if they have ToV gear.  Great choice for the "extra spot" in a grind group with their spell set and damage output.  Good spells (buffage, epic-slow, patch heals, utility spells, SNARE).  Very good at crowd control. Can have a hard time finding groups, because some sucky players gave rangers a bad rep.  Great AA advancement opportunity in archery allows for quite high-level damage output.  Not a top-tier choice for AE groups.  Post-Velious weapons are crap.<br>
<br>
Monks:  Pullers extraordinare.  High damage.  Good fit in raids.  Good in grind groups.  No CC ability.  Not a top-tier choice for AE groups.  Crappy AA advancement.  Easiest epic with stackable haste.  Many new good Luclin weapons.<br>
<br>
Rogues:  Top damage dealers.  Great raid fit.  Good in grind groups.  No CC ability.  Unwelcome in AE groups.  Second easiest epic. Crappy AA advancement.  Many new good Luclin weapons.<br>
<br>
Bards:  Great utility class.  Great for raids, and grind groups.  Always wanted...almost a member of the "holy trinity".   Many new good Luclin weapons.<br>
<br>
Beastlords.  Too early to say, but they don't look that group friendly in dungeons, and may not contribute enough to raids...because of pet pathing issues.<br>
<br>
Clerics:  Invaluable.  Member of the "holy trinity" (cleric/chanter/warrior).  AE groups.  CH ability overpowers all other healers, esp on raids.  Need I say more?<br>
<br>
Druids:  Great ultility class (heals, ports, buffage, evacs, utility spells, nukage, DoTs).  Good in grind groups, good in raids, good solo (quad kiting).  I would label druids as the "most underappreciated class", as they often have a hard time finding grind groups, but shouldn't.<br>
<br>
Shaman:  Great ultility class (heals, buffage, utility spells, DoTs, haste, slow).  Very desired in grind groups, required in raids, good solo.  Less "stackable" in raids though.<br>
<br>
Chanters:  Invaluable.  Member of the "holy trinity" (cleric/chanter/warrior).  AE groups.  Dire charm with AA investment.  Not that stackable in raids.<br>
<br>
Necros:  Another good utility class of underappreciated value.  This class lost their focus as a "mean damage dealer" post-50.  Hard time finding grind groups.  Not that stackable in raids.  Unwanted in AE groups.<br>
<br>
Wizards:  Cornerstone of AE groups.  Highly raid desired.  Soloes well (quad+ kiting).  Their evac capability and their porting abilities greatly aides their group-friendliness, but they often have a hard time finding groups.  Great AA opportunites.  Many great spells.<br>
<br>
Mages:  Pet-pathing issues greatly limit their effectiveness on raids and indoors.  Nukes are resisted too-often in raids.  Good choice in normal grind groups.  Not that welcome in AE groups.<br>
<br>
<br>
